solutions.content:
Here is a template problem of bipartite.

First we convert ```dislikes``` to a graph. And nodes from any edge can't be in the same group. Since it's bipartite, there are only two kinds of group: 0 and 1.

So we DFS each node and all of its children nodes should be in different group with it. And when we visit a visited node and there is a group conflict, then the graph can't be bipartite.
```
def possibleBipartition(N, dislikes):
	graph, group = collections.defaultdict(set), {}
	for u, v in dislikes: graph[u].add(v), graph[v].add(u)
	def dfs(node, g):
		if node in group: return group[node] == g
		group[node] = g
		return all(dfs(nei, 1-g) for nei in graph[node])
	return all(dfs(node, 0) for node in range(1,N+1) if node not in group)
```

