# Bipartite graph
a bipartite graph (or bigraph) is a graph whose vertices can be divided into two disjoint and independent sets U and V, that is every edge connects a vertex in U to one in V. Vertex sets U and V are usually called the parts of the graph.

# Test cases
![bi.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/75d09c25-7f1f-426b-9ffc-83436328399f_1671611046.255755.jpeg)

first test case is true because the graph is Bipartite graph

![bi2.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3af97ca8-1ad3-430b-9ac6-43be9467b192_1671611106.7889366.jpeg)

Second test case is false because the graph is not Bipartite graph
Because there node 2 linked with node 3 in the same part 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
using dfs .. assign a first group to node and the nodes linked with it assign a second group and so on
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
n is number of nodes 
m is number of edges 
### O(n+m)


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    set<int>g1,g2;//two parts of gragh 
    const static int N = 2009;
    vector<int>adj[N];//adjacency matrix
    bool vis[N];// boolean array to check nodes are visted or not 
    //dfs take a current node and boolean to set the node to part of gragh
    void dfs(int u, bool g){
        //Determine the node group
        (g)?g1.insert(u):g2.insert(u);
        //If visited it before then stop dfs
        if(vis[u])
            return;
        //mark is visited
        vis[u]=1;
        // Recur for all the vertices adjacent
        for(auto v:adj[u])
            //flip the boolean Because each Node is linked to Nodes in the other group
            dfs(v,g^1);
    }
    bool possibleBipartition(int n, vector<vector<int>>& dislikes) {
        //fill adjacency matrix
        for(int i=0;i<dislikes.size();i++){
            adj[dislikes[i][0]].push_back(dislikes[i][1]);
            adj[dislikes[i][1]].push_back(dislikes[i][0]);
        }
        //call dfs
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            if(!vis[i])
                dfs(i,0);
        }
        //if the number of nodes of two parts of graph = the number of all nodes
        //then the graph is Bipartite graph
        //if the number of nodes of two parts of graph > the number of all nodes 
        //then the graph is not Bipartite graph
        //Because there are some Nodes linked with nodes in the same part 
        return g1.size()+g2.size()==n;
    }
};
```

