# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
1. First thought of using union find.
2. We can merge those dislikes the same person into the same group, and check whether they dislike each other afterward.
3. Quick example:  [a] dislike [c], [b] dislike [c] => [a & b] are in the group that dislike [c].
if afterwards we got [a] dislike [b], means need to split "dislike c group" into two, thus can't make it total of two groups.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Put each into default group, and let (n + i) as group that dislike i.
2. Iterate throuth dislikes, join [a.i] to dislike [b.i] group and join [b.i]to dislike [a.i] group.
3. Check if any [a.i] and [b.i] dislke each other are in the same group.

# Complexity
Let N is number of people, M is length of dislikes.
- Time complexity: O(N + M).
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N).
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool possibleBipartition(int n, vector<vector<int>>& dislikes) {
        ++n;
        vector<int> groups(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            groups[i] = i;
        }

        for (auto& dlk: dislikes) {
            if (unionFind(dlk[0], groups) == unionFind(dlk[1], groups)) return false;
            groups[unionFind(dlk[0], groups)] = unionFind(n + dlk[1], groups);
            groups[unionFind(dlk[1], groups)] = unionFind(n + dlk[0], groups);
        }

        return true;
    }

    int unionFind(int v, vector<int>& groups) {
        if (v != groups[v]) groups[v] = unionFind(groups[v], groups);
        return groups[v];
    }
};
```

