solutions.content:
**Logic**
The logic is simple, assume the two groups are denoted as `0` and `1`, we can just assign a member `a` as either one of them,e.g. `0`, then all the members he/she dislikes has to be in the other group, it can be represented as `1 - group of(a)`. To do this, we can build a tree structure, where for a node, all its children are the member he dislikes. There maybe multiple seprate trees for the inputs

Then we just iterate the tree, make sure there is no conflict in the group, e.g. if a member is going to be in group `0`, but it has been assigned to group `1` before. Then it is a conflict, we cannot do bipartition, just `return false`. It can be done using **BFS Queue** data strucure. Refer an example blow. 

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/20010603-25e4-4358-a9a4-9bfd91566a24_1632947741.135317.jpeg)

**Others**
( I do not know why some posts used **coloring** for the explanation. It's like we have 2 group here, they interpret this to 2 **colors** , they when implementing the code, they transfer **color** to group again? It is unnessary)

---
**Code**
```java
class Solution {
    public boolean possibleBipartition(int n, int[][] dislikes) {
        if(dislikes == null || dislikes.length == 0) return true;

        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> neighbors = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i = 1; i < n + 1; i++){
            neighbors.put(i, new ArrayList<Integer>());
        }

        for(int[] dislike : dislikes){
            neighbors.get(dislike[0]).add(dislike[1]);
            neighbors.get(dislike[1]).add(dislike[0]);
        }

        // key is the node, value is the group
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(int i = 1; i < n + 1; i++){
            if(!map.containsKey(i)){
                if(checkBiPartition(i, map, neighbors) == false) return false;
            }    
        }

        return true;
    }

    public boolean checkBiPartition(int cur, Map<Integer, Integer> map, Map<Integer, List<Integer>> neighbors){
        Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();
        queue.offer(cur);
        map.put(cur, 0); // put first node in group 0

        while(!queue.isEmpty()){
            int size = queue.size();
			int curGroup = map.get(queue.peek());
			int nextGroup = 1 - curGroup;
            for(int i = 0; i < size; i++){
                int tmp = queue.poll();
                // all its neighbors, either not visisted, we put into the other group or 
                // visited: it is in the expected group
                for(int neighbor : neighbors.getOrDefault(tmp, new ArrayList<Integer>())){
                    if(!map.containsKey(neighbor)){
                        // never visted, put it into another group
                        map.put(neighbor, nextGroup));
                        queue.offer(neighbor);
                    }
                    // if it is already visited, then make sure it is the expected group 
                    if(map.get(neighbor) != nextGroup) return false;
                }
            }
        }

        return true;
    }
}
```

---
**Complexity**
TC: O(n)
SC: O(n)
Assuming `n` is the number of nodes

