This one was pretty straightforward and I am not sure why was ranked as a medium, since I can think of several "easy" on a similar level.

To solve it, we will first of all declare a couple of variables:
* `currTime` will store the current point in time we are considering a the moment, initialised to be `0`;
* `total` will store our ongoing sum of delays and it will be initialised to `0` too.

We will then loop through each item in `customers` and:
* update `currTime` to be the higher value between its previous value or the starting point of the client, plus his inherent waiting time;
* update `total`, increasing it by `currTime - c[0]` at each iteration.

Once done, we can just return `total / customers.size()`.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    double averageWaitingTime(vector<vector<int>>& customers) {
        // support variables
        int currTime = 0;
        double total = 0;
        // parsing the input
        for (auto c: customers) {
            // updating currTime and total
            currTime = max(currTime, c[0]) + c[1];;
            total += currTime - c[0];
        }
        return total / customers.size();
    }
};
```

