# Approach
We will keep track of the time the previous customer ended through prevEndTime variable declared prior to traversal. We will update this in each iteration.

For each customer:
1) Calculate the time taken for a customer which should be time time taken to prepare his food + any waiting time.
We can break down "waiting time":
the wait time of customer i = end time of previous customer - entry time of customer i.
Note that if there is no overlap between when the previous customer finishes and this new customer starts, this wait time will be negative.
So we can write wait time of i = food prep time[i] + max (0, prevEndTime - startTime[i]);
We can add this to the total wait time variable, which is used just for the average.

2) Set prevEndTime = startTime + waitTime.

Return total wait time / number of customers.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N)

- Space complexity:
O(1) auxiliary space.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    double averageWaitingTime(vector<vector<int>>& customers) {
        int prevEndTime = 0;
        double totalTimeWaited = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < customers.size(); ++i)
        {
            // If there is an overlap between last customer's end time and i's start time, add that 
            // overlap to wait time of i.
            int startTime = customers[i][0];
            int timeWaited = customers[i][1] + max (0, prevEndTime - startTime);
            // Set previous end time for next customer to the time when i finishes.
            prevEndTime = startTime + timeWaited;
            totalTimeWaited += timeWaited;
        }
        return totalTimeWaited/customers.size();
    }
};
```

