# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We need to first focus on finding just how long each customer is waiting. 
The logical way to think of it is to see what time they finished getting their order and subtract that by when they got there. 
To find when they finished getting their order, it firsts starts with the initilize time the order gets started plus the length of how long it will take to complete the order. Then we subtract the time they came to find the total time waited. 

Most of the time the chef can be busy, and since the chef can only do one order at a time, the times may overlap, hence why we must take into account when the CHEF is ready to start the order, and not when the CUSTOMER is ready to order. 

Sometimes business might be slow and the chef may have no orders to do, in those cases, the arrival time of the guest is GREATER than the time the chef is ready to start the next order. 
For example, the chef may finish an order at time 10 but not have any customers until time 15 therefore in these scenarios, the next customer only has to wait the total length of their order, without worrying about any preceeding customer wait times.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

First start off by initiizing the start of the first order, which will be when the first customer arrives. 
Then initilize a sum variable in which we will add the total wait times for each customer.
Now we start a for loop, to iterate through the matrix. We only need a single loop since we already know there are only two possible indexes for the "columns" of the matrix. 
in the loop we can store the arrival time of the current guest and the length of their order.
Then we will make an if statement to see if the chef is free right now or not. If the chef is available to start the order BEFORE the arrival of the next guest, then we will go inside of the for loop where:

We simply add the order length into our sum vairable and set the start order variable to whenever chef finishes this order.

In the else portion:
We will find out what time the chef will finish the current order by adding the next available time chef can start the order (startOrder) to the total amount of time it takes to complete the order.
Then we subtract this final time finished by what time the guests arrived to find the total time they had to wait.
Then we set the startOrder variable to the time chef finished the current order, as that is the next available time chef is to start the next order, and add on the time waited for the customer to the sum variable.

Finally we divide the sum by total number of customers to find the answer.


# Code
```
class Solution {
    public double averageWaitingTime(int[][] customers) {



        // time finished = start preparing order time + order length in time 
        //time waited = time finished - arrival time
        int startOrder = customers[0][0]; 
        double sum = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i< customers.length; i++){
            int arrivalTime = customers[i][0]; 
            int orderLength = customers[i][1]; 
            if(startOrder < arrivalTime){
                sum+= orderLength;
                startOrder = arrivalTime + orderLength;;

            }
            else{
            int timeFinished = startOrder + orderLength; 
            int timeWaited = timeFinished - arrivalTime; 
            startOrder = timeFinished; 

            sum += timeWaited; 
            }
        }
        double ans = sum / customers.length;
        return ans;


    }
}
```

