# Intuition :
To calculate the average waiting time, we need to know the waiting time for each customer. The waiting time for a customer is the time they start being served minus the time they arrived at the restaurant. We can calculate the waiting time for each customer by keeping track of the current time and updating it as we process each customer's order.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach :
1. Set the current time to the arrival time of the first customer plus the time to process their order.
1. Loop through the remaining customers:
  - If the current time is greater than or equal to the customer's arrival time, add the time to process their order to the current time and calculate their waiting time.
 - If the current time is less than the customer's arrival time, set the current time to the customer's arrival time plus the time to process their order, and calculate their waiting time.
3. Add each customer's waiting time to a vector.
4. Calculate the average waiting time by summing up all the waiting times and dividing by the number of customers.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity : The time complexity of this algorithm is $$O(n)$$, where N is the number of customers. This is because we loop through each customer once and perform constant-time operations (adding and subtracting integers) for each customer. Therefore, the time complexity is linear in the number of customers.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity : The space complexity of this algorithm is $$O(n)$$, where N is the number of customers. This is because we are storing the waiting time for each customer in a vector of size N.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    double averageWaitingTime(vector<vector<int>>& customers) {
        // Set the initial time to the arrival time of the first customer plus the time to process their order
        int currentTime = customers[0][0] + customers[0][1];

        // Create a vector to store the waiting times for each customer
        vector<int> waitTimes; 

        // Calculate the waiting time for the first customer and add it to the vector
        int currentWaitTime = currentTime - customers[0][0];
        waitTimes.push_back(currentWaitTime);

        // Loop through the remaining customers and calculate their waiting times
        for(int i=1; i<customers.size(); i++){
            if(currentTime >= customers[i][0]){
                // If the customer arrives while the restaurant is still processing the previous order,
                // add the time to process their order to the current time and calculate their waiting time
                currentTime += customers[i][1]; 
                int currentWaitTime = currentTime - customers[i][0]; 
                waitTimes.push_back(currentWaitTime); 
            }
            else{
                // If the customer arrives after the previous order has been completed,
                // set the current time to their arrival time plus the time to process their order,
                // and calculate their waiting time
                currentTime = customers[i][0] + customers[i][1]; 
                int currentWaitTime = currentTime - customers[i][0];
                waitTimes.push_back(currentWaitTime); 
            }
        }

        // Calculate the average waiting time by summing up all the waiting times and dividing by the number of customers
        double totalWaitTime = 0.0;
        for(int i=0; i<waitTimes.size(); i++){
            totalWaitTime += waitTimes[i]; 
        }
        return totalWaitTime / waitTimes.size();
    }
};

```

